    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Yeah, I see what you mean about the scope being too broad. It feels like there's a lot of room for them to find stuff to blame me for. Is there any way to make the language more \"contained\" so there aren't these hidden liabilities hiding in the fine print?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "To make it more \"contained,\" you need to narrow the scope of what you are responsible for. You should push to limit the indemnity to *direct* damages resulting *directly* from your breach, rather than every conceivable \"loss\" or \"consequence.\" You can also try to add a carve-out stating that you are *not* responsible for their own negligence. This is crucial; you don't want to be liable for their own mistakes while you're trying to keep your own obligations in check. Negotiating this down is often a battle, but it's worth the effort.",
      "source": "target",
